Here is Deon Kay. He should still be here.
‚†Ä
Deon was shot in Southeast yesterday worsening the tension between the community and the police, igniting several protests overnight.
‚†Ä
We grieve the loss with our community and will continue to ask for widespread, systematic reform to decrease violence and protect our youth. Deon celebrated his 18th birthday last month and should be here to celebrate another.
‚†Ä
We send love and support to the families and friends of Deon as well as to the entire Southeast community. We feel your frustration and your heart break. We see you. We value you. üíî

Calling all our young Black boys! Mr. Davian, our talented Vice Principal of Literacy for the Elementary academy, has received a grant to start a book club for young males grades 2-5.

This is an amazing opportunity to build your at-home libraries and have conversations about black authors and growing into a black man.

Happy Monday! We are excited to reintroduce Ms. Kelly Smith, former 6th grade math teacher, as our new Vice Principal of STEM for the Middle School Academy. She is a graduate of North Carolina A&T, first working as an assistant teacher at an alternative school, then teaching with KIPP New Orleans and KIPP DC.
‚†Ä
Fun fact:
She won 1st place on BET's 106 & Park's Wild Out Wednesday.
‚†Ä
On being a leader at IP:
She is most excited about being a model of Black Girl Magic to our students and surrounding community. With perseverance, dedication, and humility you can literally do ANYTHING you put your mind to.

post_text:
Happy Friday! Today marked Day 2 of our summer training for new staff. In the Middle School Academy we discussed the procedures and purpose of Advisory. We started the conversation with this video that talks about how Black girls can often experience school. We strive as an organization to be a safe, healing place for our girls.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g7F9XCdeOtw

Check out the video and here are a few of our favorite quotes that capture some of our feelings around our work:

‚ÄúEducation is freedom work. When girls feel safe, they can learn.‚Äù

‚ÄúContinue to do the deep internal work to address biases.‚Äù

‚ÄúProvide children with the opportunity to heal so they can learn.‚Äù

‚ÄúWe can shift educational conditions so that no girl is pushed out of school. That‚Äôs a win for all of us.‚Äù
shared_text:
YOUTUBE.COM
Why black girls are targeted for punishment at school -- and how to change that | Monique W. Morris

IP Families, this morning Mayor Bowser updated guidance on school closures for D.C. such that schools -- including Ingenuity Prep -- will be closed for students through the end of the school year.

With this extension of the closure window, we will continue executing on our distance learning plan for students.
As of now, we have not made a decision about when school will end for SY19-20 or whether we are changing the first day of the SY20-21 school year.

However, now that we have certainty in regards to students returning in SY19-20, we can begin to make decisions about how we best move forward for the remainder of this school year and beyond.

We anticipate finalizing some of these decisions in the coming weeks and we‚Äôll share updates with you as we have them.

For now though, it‚Äôs full steam ahead on our distance learning work restarting up Monday. And with Spring Break ending, food service and front desk coverage will restart on Monday, as well. Please reach our front desk staff at (202) 562-0391 if there is anything we can help with.

shared_text:
DC Public Charter School Board
December 19, 2019 at 3:15 PM ¬∑

Teacher Spotlight Thursday: Meet Ms. Roberts üìö

Ms. Roberts is a third-grade literacy teacher at Ingenuity Prep PCS. Aside from her phenomenal literacy instruction, Ms. Roberts is known around the building for the love she has for all students. She often goes out of her way to build strong relationships with students who aren't in her class to ensure that on their toughest days they have an extra adult that they can come and talk with. Ms. Roberts is constantly striving to improve her practice and is currently working to complete her master's degree in special education at American University so that she can better serve her students with special needs! #DCcharterProud

We are excited to launch our partnership with Carpool to School. Carpool to School makes it easier and more convenient to connect with other parents to organize car and walking pools.

Carpool to School is available only to Ingenuity Prep families and will make it easier to plan rides or walking groups for students to get to school. Once registered and approved, families can find other families based on distance, schedule, and student‚Äôs grade to coordinate getting to and from school.

Please visit www.ingenuityprep.org/carpooltoschool to register today.
